SIMPLE: what
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: What
<hw>What</hw> <pr>(hw⟦ocr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>pron., a., & adv.</pos>
<ety>[AS. <ets>hw⟦ae⟧t</ets>, neuter of <ets>hw⟦amac⟧</ets> who; akin to
OS. <ets>hwat</ets> what, OFries. <ets>hwet</ets>, D. & LG.
<ets>wat</ets>, G. <ets>was</ets>, OHG. <ets>waz</ets>, <ets>hwaz</ets>,
Icel. <ets>hvat</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>hvad</ets>, Goth. <ets>hwa</ets>.
⟦root⟧182. See <er>Who</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>As an interrogative pronoun, used in asking
questions regarding either persons or things; <as>as, <ex>what</ex> is
this? <ex>what</ex> did you say? <ex>what</ex> poem is this?
<ex>what</ex> child is lost?</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>What</qex> see'st thou in the ground?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>What</qex> is man, that thou art mindful of him?</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. viii. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>What</qex> manner of man is this, that even the winds and the
sea obey him!</q> <rj><qau>Matt. viii. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ Originally, <xex>what</xex>, <xex>when</xex>,
<xex>where</xex>, <xex>which</xex>, <xex>who</xex>, <xex>why</xex>,
etc., were interrogatives only, and it is often difficult to determine
whether they are used as interrogatives or relatives.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p> <xex>What</xex> in this sense, when it refers to things, may be used
either substantively or adjectively; when it refers to persons, it is
used only adjectively with a noun expressed, <xex>who</xex> being the
pronoun used substantively.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>As an exclamatory word: -- <sd>(a)</sd> Used
absolutely or independently; -- often with a question following.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>What</xex> welcome be thou.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>What</qex>, could ye not watch with me one hour?</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xxvi. 40.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Used adjectively, meaning <xex>how
remarkable</xex>, or <xex>how great</xex>; <as>as, <ex>what</ex> folly!
<ex>what</ex> eloquence! <ex>what</ex> courage!</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>What</qex> a piece of work is man!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O <qex>what</qex> a riddle of absurdity!</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>What</xex> in this use has <xex>a</xex> or
<xex>an</xex> between itself and its noun if the qualitative or
quantitative importance of the object is emphasized.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>Sometimes prefixed to adjectives in an adverbial
sense, as nearly equivalent to <xex>how</xex>; <as>as, <ex>what</ex>
happy boys!</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>What</qex> partial judges are our love and hate!</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>As a relative pronoun</def>: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>Used substantively with the antecedent suppressed,
equivalent to <xex>that which</xex>, or <xex>those</xex> [persons]
<xex>who</xex>, or <xex>those</xex> [things] <xex>which</xex>; -- called
a <xex>compound relative</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With joy beyond <qex>what</qex> victory bestows.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'm thinking Captain Lawton will count the noses of
<qex>what</qex> are left before they see their whaleboats.</q>
<rj><qau>Cooper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>What</qex> followed was in perfect harmony with this
beginning.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I know well . . . how little you will be disposed to criticise
<qex>what</qex> comes to you from me.</q> <rj><qau>J. H.
Newman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Used adjectively, equivalent to <xex>the</xex> . .
. <xex>which</xex>; <xex>the sort</xex> or <xex>kind of</xex> . . .
<xex>which</xex>; rarely, <xex>the</xex> . . . <xex>on</xex>, or
<xex>at</xex>, <xex>which</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>See <qex>what</qex> natures accompany <qex>what</qex> colors.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To restrain <qex>what</qex> power either the devil or any earthly
enemy hath to work us woe.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We know <qex>what</qex> master laid thy keel,⟦br⟧
<qex>What</qex> workmen wrought thy ribs of steel.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>Used adverbially in a sense corresponding to the
adjectival use; <as>as, he picked <ex>what</ex> good fruit he
saw</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Whatever; whatsoever; what thing soever; -- used
indefinitely.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>What</xex> after so befall.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether it were the shortness of his foresight, the strength of
his will, . . . or <qex>what</qex> it was.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Used adverbially, in part; partly; somewhat; -- with
a following preposition, especially, <xex>with</xex>, and commonly with
repetition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>What</qex> for lust [pleasure] and <qex>what</qex> for
lore.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus, <qex>what</qex> with the war, <qex>what</qex> with the
sweat, <qex>what</qex> with the gallows, and <qex>what</qex> with
poverty, I am custom shrunk.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The year before he had so used the matter that <qex>what</qex> by
force, <qex>what</qex> by policy, he had taken from the Christians above
thirty small castles.</q> <rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ In such phrases as <xex>I tell you what</xex>,
<xex>what</xex> anticipates the following statement, being elliptical
for <xex>what I think</xex>, <xex>what it is</xex>, <xex>how it
is</xex>, etc. ⟦ldquo⟧I tell thee <xex>what</xex>, corporal Bardolph, I
could tear her.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> Here <xex>what</xex> relates to
the last clause, ⟦ldquo⟧I could tear her;⟦rdquo⟧ this is what I tell
you.⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<xex>What not</xex> is often used at the close of an enumeration of
several particulars or articles, it being an abbreviated clause, the
verb of which, being either the same as that of the principal clause or
a general word, as <xex>be</xex>, <xex>say</xex>, <xex>mention</xex>,
<xex>enumerate</xex>, etc., is omitted. ⟦ldquo⟧Men hunt, hawk, and
<xex>what not</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Becon.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Some dead puppy, or
log, or <xex>what not</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>C. Kingsley.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧Battles, tournaments, hunts, and <xex>what not</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>De Quincey.</au> Hence, the words are often used in a general sense
with the force of a substantive, equivalent to <xex>anything you
please</xex>, <xex>a miscellany</xex>, <xex>a variety</xex>, etc. From
this arises the name <xex>whatnot</xex>, applied to an
<xex>⟦eacute⟧tag⟦egrave⟧re</xex>, as being a piece of furniture intended
for receiving miscellaneous articles of use or ornament. <-- also called
a whatnot shelf -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p> <xex>But what</xex> is used for <xex>but that</xex>, usually after a
negative, and excludes everything contrary to the assertion in the
following sentence. ⟦ldquo⟧Her needle is not so absolutely perfect in
tent and cross stitch <xex>but what</xex> my superintendence is
advisable.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir W. Scott.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Never fear <xex>but
what</xex> our kite shall fly as high.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Ld.
Lytton.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<cs><p><col><b>What ho!</b></col> <cd>an exclamation of calling.</cd> --
<col><b>What if</b></col>, <cd>what will it matter if; what will happen
or be the result if.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>What if</xex> it be a
poison?⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>What of this?</b></col>
<col><b>What of that?</b></col> <col><b>What of it?</b></col>
etc.</mcol>, <cd>what follows from this, that, it, etc., often with the
implication that it is of no consequence; so what?</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧All this
is so; but <xex>what of this</xex>, my lord?⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧The night is spent, why, <xex>what of that</xex>?⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>What though</b></col>, <cd>even granting that;
allowing that; supposing it true that.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>What
though</xex> the rose have prickles, yet't is plucked.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>What time</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>What time as</b></col></mcol>, <cd>when.</cd> <mark>[Obs. or
Archaic]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>What time</xex> I am afraid, I will trust in
thee.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Ps. lvi. 3.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>What time</qex> the morn mysterious visions brings.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>What</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: What
<hw>What</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Something; thing;
stuff.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And gave him for to feed,⟦br⟧
Such homely <qex>what</qex> as serves the simple clown.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>What</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: What
<hw>What</hw>, <pos>interrog. adv.</pos> <def>Why? For what purpose? On
what account?</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>What</qex> should I tell the answer of the knight.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But <qex>what</qex> do I stand reckoning upon advantages and gains
lost by the misrule and turbulency of the prelates? <qex>What</qex> do I
pick up so thriftily their scatterings and diminishings of the meaner
subject?</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>whatchamacallit</ent>⟦br⟧
